While we find no evidence for a positive feedback of summer warming that would trigger an abrupt runaway seed production, our results suggest possible changes in synchrony as we lose the cold summers---the potential hinge points for population synchronization. Several consecutive years without cold summers could progressively decrease synchrony within a population (Fig. \ref{fig:hinge}). This result is consistent with our previous finding that only \Sexpr{round(kq$mastingtrees_warmfuture['50%'],1)}\% of trees mast in years with very warm summers (Fig. \ref{fig:future}), resulting in low synchrony---whereas synchrony would remain high if all trees were stuck in a high reproductive state every year. Determining the extent to which this will happen in the coming decades, and producing robust spatiotemporal forecasts, will require improved metrics of synchrony and better measurements of the scale at which synchrony appears and disappears across years (CITE?). %emw17Feb -- Sure, can you tell the reader how to do that? If not, this feels a broad sweeping argument missing a hint of how to do this *in* a paper all about how to better model this stuff. Maybe you could walk the reader quickly through what this model can do? I suspect it's improved metrics of syncrhony and the spatial scale? Then you could mention measurements separately but give a hint on what you actually want for measurements (does this model suggest any?) ... or do you just mean what you mention below in which case skip it here (or skip it here either way and move it down to keep the ideas together). [Or, wait, maybe you or I have just made my mistake of putting the next paragraph's topic sentence at the end of the last paragraph? ]

